"# Chapter 14 — Modules (Importing What You Need)

Motoi comes in two halves.

**CORE** is what you've been using for thirteen chapters. About 335 verbs. Always loaded. Every kid-friendly primitive — arithmetic, lists, functions, macros, entities, grid, cortex, audio basics.

**Modules** are the rest — specialized packs that ship alongside CORE but aren't loaded until you ask. Advanced music. Advanced geometry. Physics simulation. Chemistry. Discrete math. Advanced AI (behavior trees, steering behaviors). Cameras with follow-and-shake. Sixteen modules in total, adding about 574 more verbs.

You don't need modules to write a first game. You'll want them the moment you need something CORE doesn't cover: an FFT for audio analysis, a Bezier curve for smooth motion, a molar-mass calculator for chemistry homework, or a set of vintage drum-machine emulations.

## The module list

Sixteen modules, grouped by area:

**Math**
- `math-advanced` — 220 verbs. Advanced arithmetic, statistics, FFT, matrices.
- `math-discrete` — 88 verbs. Combinatorics, graph algorithms, number theory.
- `math-topology` — 27 verbs. Sets, connected components.
- `math-geometry-advanced` — 37 verbs. Cones, spheres, transforms, law-of-cosines.
- `math-curves` — 37 verbs. Bezier, spline, easing curves.
- `math-plot` — 14 verbs. Plotting, axes, histograms.

**Science**
- `science-physics` — 19 verbs. Momentum, force, gravity constants.
- `science-chemistry` — 5 verbs. Molar mass, moles.

**Music**
- `music-advanced` — 12 verbs. Vintage kits, transport, patterns, tick oscillators.

**Games**
- `game-advanced` — 21 verbs. Advanced sprites, layers, particles.
- `game-entity-advanced` — 20 verbs. Health, damage, AI hooks.
- `game-world-advanced` — 20 verbs. World zones, spawners, waves.
- `game-ai-advanced` — 14 verbs. Behavior trees, steering, flocking.
- `game-camera-advanced` — 9 verbs. Camera follow, shake, panning.
- `game-juggle` — 6 verbs. Timing multiple entities.

**Utility**
- `compat-legacy` — legacy verb aliases from older Motoi versions.

You can see the whole set at `modules/` inside your Motoi installation. Each folder has a `MANIFEST.slat` describing it and a `reference.slat` naming each verb.

## The intended shape: `import`

The design vision is that you write:

```
(import (motoi music advanced))

;; Now you can call the new verbs
(synth/808 'kick)   ;; a vintage 808 kick, hypothetical
```

That syntax is *coming* — the runtime is being wired to resolve `(motoi music advanced)` to `modules/music-advanced/MANIFEST.slat` and load its verbs on demand. At the time of this book, `import` isn't quite there yet — but the machinery is close.

## Today's behavior: everything loaded

Right now, in the current version of `motoi`, when you run `motoi eval` or `motoi run` or `motoi repl`, the runtime loads *all* the modules for you. That's why you've been able to use `math/lerp` (CORE), `math/sqrt` (CORE), `geom/sin` (CORE), and even `geom/distance` (part of the advanced geometry module) without ever writing an import.

```
$ motoi eval \"(math/lerp 0 100 0.5)\"
50

$ motoi eval \"(geom/distance '(0 0) '(3 4))\"
5
```

Both work. Some verbs live in CORE; some live in modules; but from the terminal, the difference isn't visible. That's a design choice — kid-friendly, no import ceremony, everything Just Works.

Once the on-demand loader lands, you'll be able to *opt out* of modules — starting from CORE-only with `motoi --core-only` and importing what you need. That's better for large programs where load time matters, and better for training the runtime's built-in Copilot (which learns CORE by heart and looks up modules on demand).

## Reading a MANIFEST

Every module has a `MANIFEST.slat` describing it. Peek at one:

```
$ cat modules/music-advanced/MANIFEST.slat
(manifest
  :name          \"(motoi music advanced)\"
  :folder        \"modules/music-advanced/\"
  :version       \"1.0.0\"
  :verb-count    12
  :libraries     [\"synth-advanced\",\"transport\",\"pattern\",\"tick-advanced\"]
  ...)
```

Key things a MANIFEST tells you:
- `:name` — the import path you'll use.
- `:verb-count` — how many new verbs.
- `:libraries` — the internal JS submodules.
- `:reasoning` — a plain-English note on what the module is for.
- `:reference-file` — the file naming every verb this module adds.

Reading `MANIFEST.slat` is how you decide whether a module has what you need.

## Reading a module's reference

Each module has a `reference.slat` — a SLAT with one record per verb. Every entry tells you the verb name, its arguments, and an example.

```
$ head -30 modules/music-advanced/reference.slat
```

You get a flat list of verbs. Search it with grep, or open it in your editor. This is a *reference*, not a tutorial — for concepts you'd want the module's own docs (when they exist) or the CORE tutorial (which is this book).

## Using module verbs today

Since everything's loaded, you can just call module verbs directly. For example, if you wanted a Bezier ease (from `math-curves`):

```
(bezier-ease 0.5)
```

That's a CORE verb name — `bezier-ease` — but the implementation is in the curves module. From your code's point of view, no difference.

If you're unsure what module a verb comes from, look it up in the reference SLAT. Every entry has a `:library` field naming the source.

## When to reach for a module

A rough guide:

**Reach for `math-advanced`** when you need statistics, matrix math, FFTs, or any of the more grown-up math.

**Reach for `math-curves`** when you want smooth interpolation beyond `math/lerp` — Bezier for animation curves, spring for bouncy easing.

**Reach for `game-ai-advanced`** when you're building an enemy that needs to *decide* things — a behavior tree, a steering behavior, flocking.

**Reach for `game-world-advanced`** when your world has multiple zones or you're spawning enemies in waves.

**Reach for `game-camera-advanced`** when you want the view to follow a hero, shake on impact, or pan smoothly.

**Reach for `music-advanced`** when you want vintage drum machines, precise transport control, or advanced patterns.

For a *first* game, CORE is more than enough. Modules become interesting once you know what you're missing.

## An example using a module verb

The easing family in the curves module reshapes a linear time value into a natural-feeling motion curve. In Motoi you call them through `named-ease`, which takes a `t` value (0..1) and an ease name.

```
(named-ease 0.5 'linear)      ;; => 0.5
(named-ease 0.5 'ease-in)     ;; => 0.315…  (moves slowly at first)
(named-ease 0.5 'ease-out)    ;; => 0.684…  (moves fast at first, decelerates)
(named-ease 0.5 'ease-in-out) ;; => 0.5     (mostly-linear at midpoint)
```

Use them anywhere you'd use `t` in a lerp:

```
(let* ((frame 10)
       (total 30)
       (t (/ frame total))
       (eased (named-ease t 'ease-in-out))
       (x (math/lerp 0 200 eased)))
  x)
```

Linear interp with `t` gives you a mechanical, robotic motion. Interp with `(named-ease t 'ease-in-out)` gives you the smooth accelerate-then-decelerate motion that feels natural — the way things move in the real world.

## Module discipline

A couple of habits worth building.

**Only reach for modules when you actually need what they add.** CORE is deliberately small so the language stays learnable. Reaching for modules should feel like *upgrading*, not defaulting.

**When you do use a module verb, note it.** Somewhere in your file, near the top, a comment: `;; uses (motoi music advanced) verbs — synth/808, transport/*`. When `import` fully lands, you'll turn those comments into real imports. In the meantime, the comments are documentation and future breadcrumbs.

**Read the manifest before assuming a module has what you want.** Module scopes are curated. `math-curves` has Bezier and easing, but not FFT. `math-advanced` has FFT. Guessing which module has what wastes time; reading the manifest doesn't.

## What you know now

- CORE is 335 verbs, always loaded — everything you've used through Chapter 13.
- Modules are 16 packs adding 574 more verbs, thematic groupings around math, science, music, and games.
- Today, `motoi` loads all modules by default — you can call module verbs directly.
- The future syntax `(import (motoi music advanced))` will opt in explicitly per program.
- Each module has a `MANIFEST.slat` (metadata) and a `reference.slat` (verb list).
- `easing/*` are the most immediately useful module verbs — smooth animation curves.
- CORE is enough for a first game; reach for modules when you know what CORE doesn't have.

## Try before you turn the page

1. Open `modules/README.slat` and read the full list of modules. Note which ones look interesting for what you might build.

2. Try each easing on `t = 0.5` using `named-ease`: `'linear`, `'ease-in`, `'ease-out`, `'ease-in-out`, `'emphasized`. Print each result.

3. Use `(named-ease t 'ease-in-out)` in a real animation loop — move a dot from x=0 to x=100 over 30 frames, using ease-in-out on the fraction. Print positions. Compare with the same loop using linear interp.

4. Peek at `modules/game-ai-advanced/reference.slat` — spot verbs starting with `ai/bt-*` (behavior tree) and `ai/*` (steering). You don't have to use them yet — just see what's there.

5. Design a hypothetical module of your own. What five verbs would `(motoi bird-watching)` provide? What would `(motoi kitchen)` do?

## What's next

Chapter 15: **making your own module**. You've seen what modules *are* and how to use them. Chapter 15 shows you how to *build* one — a small file, a manifest, a verb or two, and instructions for how to point Motoi at it. By the end you'll have shipped your first module of the language.")
